International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 11 Jun 2011
Source: GIDEON (Global Infectious Disease & Epidemiology Network)
[edited]
http://www.gideononline.com


[re: ProMED-mail Schistosomiasis - Philippines: (LE) 20110610.1761]
-------------------------------------------------------------------
The following background data on schistosomiasis in the Philippines
are abstracted from the Gideon e-book series. [1,2] (Primary
references available on request).

Time and place
--------------
Schistosomiasis was first reported in the Philippines in 1906.
During the 1970's schistosomiasis was endemic to:
- Mindoro Oriental and Sorsogon in Southern Luzon
- The provinces of North, East, and Western Samar
- Leyte
- Bohol in Eastern Visayas
- All the provinces of Mindanao with the exception of Misamis
Oriental, Davao Oriental, and Maguindanao.

The disease is currently most common in Bohol, Lake Naujan, coastal
Mindanao, Samar, and southeastern Luzon.

Incidence and prevalence
------------------------
- In 1921, an estimated 25 000 to 30 000 people were infested -- this
number had increased to 300 000 by 1948.
- 10 million live in endemic areas, as of 2002, an estimated 800 000
were infested and 6.7 million were at risk.
- As of 2010, an estimated 560 000 persons were infested.
- 12 273 cases of schistosomiasis were officially reported in 1988;
4240 in 2000; 6628 in 2004; 9383 in 2005; 3517 in 2006
- 301 deaths were ascribed to schistosomiasis in 1988.

Reservoirs
----------
- Infection is common among dogs.
- Infection is common among field water buffaloes and rats on Leyte.
- The local snail reservoir is _Oncomelania hupensis quadrasi_.

Prevalence surveys
------------------
- 36 percent in rice farming villages on Leyte (2005 publication)
- 20 percent in Mindanao, Leyte, Samar, and Mindoro (1941)
- 16 percent in Malay-balay, Mindanao (1981 publication)
- 20 percent in Oriental Mindoro (1978)
- 15 percent in North Samar (1977 publication)
- 49.5 percent in Bolos and Gamapin barangays (rural Luzon, 1978)
- 80 percent of children in eastern Leyte (1945)
- 17.4 percent of humans, 0.5 percent of cats, 7 percent of dogs, 0.1
percent of pigs, 37.6 percent of rats, and 0.1 percent of water
buffalo in Western Samar (2003 to 2004)
- 1.6 percent to 86.3 percent of dogs, 0.1 percent to 21.7 percent of
cats, 0.01 percent to 18.4 percent of pigs, 0.1 percent to 72.5
percent of water buffaloes, and 0.7 percent to 95.4 percent of rats in
Samar Province (2007 publication)
- 0 percent to 45.2 percent of rural villagers in Samar Province
(2003 to 2004)
- 5 percent in Trinidad and Talibon townships, Bohol Province (1980
publication)
- 10 percent in Surigao del Norte (2005)
- 10 percent to 15 percent of pigs and water buffalo in endemic
areas.
- 1.6 percent to 86.3 percent of dogs in 50 endemic villages, 0.1
percent of 21.7 percent, 0.01 percent to 18.4 percent of pigs, less
than 0.1 percent to 72.5 percent of water buffaloes, and 0.7 percent
to 95.4 percent of rats. (Samar Province, 2007 publication)
- 51.5 percent of buffaloes in Macanip, Leyte (PCR, 2008)

Notable outbreaks
-----------------
1944 to 1945: an outbreak (1700 cases) was reported among United
States and Australian Army personnel (174 cases) serving in the
Philippines.
2000: an "outbreak" was reported in Davao del Sur, with 222 cases as
of October -- most in the barangays of Digos- Igpit, Colorado, and
Matti.

References
----------
1. Berger SA: Infectious Diseases of the Philippines, 2011. 379 pp,
72 graphs, 1264 references. Gideon e-book series.
http://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/country/infectious-diseases-of-the-philippines/.
2. Berger SA: _Schistosoma japonicum_: Global Status, 2011. 14 pp,
Gideon e-book series.
http://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/disease/schistosoma-japonicum-global-status/.

